## What happened

Apple's security frameworks (`Security.framework` / `CryptoKit`) **do not support DSA**. In .NET 11, the managed DSA shim that previously fell back to OpenSSL on macOS was removed (or the platform-guard was tightened), so `DSA.Create()` now throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.

## How to fix it

You have two options, in order of preference:

### Option 1 – Migrate off DSA (recommended)
DSA is a legacy algorithm (FIPS 186-4 withdrew DSA for new signatures). If you only **verify** old signatures, do a one-time re-sign with a modern algorithm (ECDSA / Ed25519 / RSA-PSS) and drop the DSA dependency entirely.

### Option 2 – Use OpenSSL explicitly on macOS
If you must keep verifying existing DSA signatures, reference OpenSSL directly:

```csharp
using System.Security.Cryptography;
using System.Runtime.InteropServices;

DSA CreateDsa()
{
    if (RuntimeInformation.IsOSPlatform(OSPlatform.OSX))
    {
        // Requires OpenSSL installed (e.g. via Homebrew: brew install openssl)
        return new DSAOpenSsl();
    }
    return DSA.Create();
}
```

Make sure OpenSSL is available on your macOS CI/CD agents:

```bash
brew install openssl
# .NET locates libssl automatically via default search paths;
# if not, set DOTNET_SYSTEM_SECURITY_CRYPTOGRAPHY_OPENSSLPATH
```

### Summary

| | Linux | Windows | macOS |
|---|---|---|---|
| `DSA.Create()` | ✅ (OpenSSL) | ✅ (CNG) | ❌ `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `new DSAOpenSsl()` | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ (needs `brew install openssl`) |

Long-term, plan to migrate away from DSA entirely—it's deprecated across the industry.
